Japan, China, Thailand, Taiwan, Philippines: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview

-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 
2011-05-09T22:29:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-09/japan-china-thailand-taiwan-philippines-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Edano will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The  Finance Ministry  will announce at 10:30 a.m. in Tokyo
the amount of 40-year Japanese  government bonds  it plans to sell
on May 17.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.14 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 80.30 per dollar at 7:26 a.m. in Tokyo.  China : Exports rose 29.5 percent in April from a year
earlier, compared with a 35.8 percent gain the previous month,
according to the median estimate of economists in a Bloomberg
survey. Imports climbed 28.9 percent during the same period, the
most since January.  Agricultural Development Bank will sell 10 billion yuan
($1.5 billion) of one-year bonds.  The yield on the 3.83 percent bond due March 2021 was 3.87
percent, according to Chinabond, the nation’s biggest debt-
clearing house. The yuan was at 6.4965.  Philippines : Exports gained 7.5 percent in March from a
year earlier, the slowest growth since November 2009, according
to the median estimate of economists in a Bloomberg survey
before data due today.  The government will sell 9 billion pesos ($210 million) of
seven-year bonds today.  The yield on the 6.50 percent bond due April 2021 was 6.45
percent, according to Tradition Financial Services. The peso was
at 42.93.  Thailand : The Bank of Thailand will sell a combined 62
billion baht ($2.1 billion) of 28-, 91- and 182-day bills, and
25 billion baht of three-year bonds.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.46 percent. The baht was at 30.20 per dollar.  Indonesia: The government will sell an unspecified amount
of five-, 10- and 15-year Islamic bonds.  The yield on the 8.25 percent bond due July 2021 was 7.72
percent. The rupiah was at 8,558.  Taiwan: The government will sell NT$30 billion ($1 billion)
of 30-year securities today.  The yield on the 1.375 percent bond due March 2021 was 1.38
percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The  Taiwan
dollar  was at NT$28.75.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Andrea Wong in Taipei at 
